None of my friends wanna
be seen with headband girl.

54:11.560 --> 54:12.719
Bitches.

54:12.720 --> 54:14.209
Bitches.
Bitches.

54:14.210 --> 54:15.210
Hey.

54:18.410 --> 54:20.110
How'd you get on the watch list?

54:21.030 --> 54:22.593
Married a big producer.

54:23.920 --> 54:25.209
Shouldn't have signed that prenup.

54:25.210 --> 54:28.693
All I got to keep were the
clothes, which are fabulous.

54:29.590 --> 54:30.590
I just

54:31.830 --> 54:34.773
don't feel like reaching out
to people like I used to.

54:36.700 --> 54:38.369
Can I tell you guys a secret?

54:38.370 --> 54:39.370
Uh-huh.

54:40.300 --> 54:42.459
Last month, I didn't go to my

54:42.460 --> 54:44.959
best friend's birthday party.

54:44.960 --> 54:47.259
Bingo, there you go.

54:47.260 --> 54:48.093
What?

54:48.093 --> 54:49.080
Your red flag.

54:49.080 --> 54:49.950
Hm-hmm.

54:49.951 --> 54:52.469
Were you invited to this party online?

54:52.470 --> 54:56.289
Yeah, but I didn't RSVP either way.

54:56.290 --> 54:58.299
I mean, no one does, right?

54:58.300 --> 54:59.579
It doesn't matter, though.

54:59.580 --> 55:01.139
You didn't show up at your best friend's

55:01.140 --> 55:04.059
publicly posted birthday
party, which means that

55:04.060 --> 55:05.053
your cellphone wasn't there, either.

55:05.054 --> 55:07.989
And that's the cellphone
that happens to track

55:07.990 --> 55:10.879
every single location of your
body on this planet Earth.

55:10.880 --> 55:12.999
Welcome to the future.

55:13.000 --> 55:14.529
Could be worse.

55:14.530 --> 55:16.203
Pretty sure my son turned me in.

55:17.180 --> 55:18.120
Ouch.

55:18.121 --> 55:19.839
Really?

55:19.840 --> 55:22.623
I was on house arrest
for a couple years.

55:23.540 --> 55:25.019
My wife left somewhere in there,

55:25.020 --> 55:26.959
and Kiefer decided to go with her.

55:26.960 --> 55:28.363
Can't say that I blame him.

55:29.200 --> 55:30.300
Neither do I.

55:30.983 --> 55:32.033
If you named him Kiefer.

55:39.010 --> 55:40.963
After the house arrest ended,

55:42.410 --> 55:44.269
I could see the alarm on his face

55:44.270 --> 55:45.513
at the state of my life.

55:47.050 --> 55:48.789
Guess he figured his old
man needed a headband

55:48.790 --> 55:50.590
to go along with the ankle bracelet.

55:52.080 --> 55:56.154
Maybe what he did was misguided, but

55:56.155 --> 55:58.959
then again, no kid his age should have

55:58.960 --> 56:00.142
to look out for his father.

56:00.600 --> 56:02.283
Are you mad at him?

56:02.700 --> 56:03.750
I'm not mad at him.

56:05.460 --> 56:06.737
Does he know that?

56:09.023 --> 56:10.573
I mean, he has to.

56:11.750 --> 56:12.852
Right?

56:19.210 --> 56:20.773
I was in a dark place.

56:22.819 --> 56:23.819
I still am, but

56:26.131 --> 56:27.163
not like I was.

56:34.490 --> 56:37.390
Well I thought they were
playing a practical joke on me.

56:39.540 --> 56:42.099
I thought, you know, one
of my old college buddies

56:42.100 --> 56:44.899
had sent me a fake court summons, right?

56:44.900 --> 56:46.839
So I start calling all those fuckers

56:46.840 --> 56:50.693
and saying, hey, who sent
me the fake court summons?

56:51.920 --> 56:54.839
And then I realized that
I hadn't talked to them

56:54.840 --> 56:57.169
in like years, and the thing is,

56:57.170 --> 56:59.170
they're all still talking to each other.

57:00.350 --> 57:02.793
So they start all asking
me the question, you know?

57:03.890 --> 57:05.633
What are you up to these days, man?

57:06.800 --> 57:09.839
I hate that question.

57:09.840 --> 57:12.329
That's like the second question
that anybody ever asks you

57:12.330 --> 57:13.480
after what's your name?

57:14.380 --> 57:15.459
What are you up to these days?

57:15.460 --> 57:16.623
Hi, I'm Lincoln, I,

57:18.610 --> 57:19.953
I used to do something.

57:21.250 --> 57:22.250
I used to

57:23.400 --> 57:25.483
love something.

57:27.830 --> 57:30.687
And now, I work in the mall.

57:34.490 --> 57:36.879
And then I wear this every day.

57:36.880 --> 57:38.763
I don't have a story.

57:39.860 --> 57:42.063
I enjoy watering my plants,

57:42.920 --> 57:44.243
and I have a cat,

57:45.460 --> 57:47.669
and I actually shush people at the library

57:47.670 --> 57:49.070
when they're being too loud.

57:50.320 --> 57:52.549
Maybe it's the result
of being the only person

57:52.550 --> 57:55.109
from Texarkana that likes goth rock.

57:55.110 --> 57:58.289
There's no way they're
gonna pass me by, either.

57:58.290 --> 58:01.399
I have zero interest in social etiquette.

58:01.400 --> 58:04.653
I say exactly what I'm
thinking at all times.

58:06.010 --> 58:09.723
I would think that would bring
me respect and popularity.

58:10.630 --> 58:13.653
Instead, I'm sitting here
with you fucking losers.

58:14.590 --> 58:16.699
From the beginning, I
vowed that I would never let

58:16.700 --> 58:18.709
anything the government
had to say about me

58:18.710 --> 58:20.629
make me change who I am.

58:20.630 --> 58:21.759
Me too.

58:21.760 --> 58:22.956
Fuck that noise.

58:22.957 --> 58:23.997
Assholes.

58:23.998 --> 58:24.998
Yeah.

58:26.526 --> 58:27.723
But maybe they're right.

58:28.760 --> 58:29.833
Just a little bit,

58:30.700 --> 58:31.743
by mistake.

58:33.100 --> 58:34.889
I've heard that even really social people

58:34.890 --> 58:37.099
need alone time now and then.

58:37.100 --> 58:38.593
Doesn't it go both ways?

58:40.000 --> 58:42.529
It'd be nice to be able to
take a break from who I am

58:42.530 --> 58:45.939
once in a while without
feeling like I'm selling out.

58:45.940 --> 58:49.313
Good God, let's stop
being so hard on ourselves.

58:50.530 --> 58:52.950
Let's take a little bit of
solace in the fact that we

58:58.544 --> 58:59.377
have had these little meetings
together for a long time

58:59.377 --> 59:00.210
without those douche bag
feds finding out about it.

59:00.211 --> 59:01.699
It's pretty good.

59:01.700 --> 59:02.859
Fuck the feds.

59:02.860 --> 59:03.860
Yeah.

59:04.872 --> 59:07.817
Fuck the feds.
Fuck the feds.

59:07.818 --> 59:09.988
Fuck the feds, fuck the feds,

59:09.989 --> 59:12.039
fuck the feds, fuck the feds.

59:12.040 --> 59:15.509
I will literally give you
everything in my savings account

59:15.510 --> 59:17.357
if we can go in and bust them right now,

59:17.358 --> 59:19.090
and I'm talking like $2,300.

59:19.091 --> 59:20.091
Shhhh.

59:21.921 --> 59:25.533
Dabney, do you have
anything you wanna say?

59:28.170 --> 59:29.319
Not really.

59:29.320 --> 59:31.629
Come on, Dabbers,
there's got to be something

59:31.630 --> 59:33.379
in that big brain you wanna share.

59:33.380 --> 59:37.121
Other than what you
do for a living, please.

59:37.122 --> 59:38.649
I think it's pretty clear that we are

59:38.650 --> 59:41.149
in a judgment-free zone here.

59:41.150 --> 59:42.229
Except for me.

59:42.230 --> 59:45.453
I'm judging you, I don't
have an off switch.

59:47.358 --> 59:49.443
Come on, come on.

59:51.600 --> 59:53.600
I definitely belong on the watch list.

59:54.530 --> 59:57.199
I'm single, I spend most of my time alone.

59:57.200 --> 01:00:00.229
I often feel misunderstood and frustrated

01:00:00.230 --> 01:00:03.299
why the rest of society
never seems to appreciate me.

01:00:03.300 --> 01:00:05.063
Or even notice me.

01:00:08.570 --> 01:00:12.393
One way that I differ from most loners is,

01:00:15.603 --> 01:00:17.453
I would actually like to have friends

01:00:18.770 --> 01:00:19.820
and be around people.

01:00:21.560 --> 01:00:22.560
They just,

01:00:23.310 --> 01:00:24.423
just never really, uh,

01:00:26.850 --> 01:00:27.850
seem to

01:00:29.340 --> 01:00:30.433
like me very much.

01:00:37.040 --> 01:00:38.040
Hey, Dabney?

01:00:42.450 --> 01:00:43.450
I like you.

01:01:09.740 --> 01:01:10.573
Yes.

01:01:10.574 --> 01:01:15.460
Sir, uh, something
is, something's happening.

01:01:19.330 --> 01:01:20.679
Yes?

01:01:20.680 --> 01:01:23.299
I don't know if it's
a good or a bad thing.

01:01:23.300 --> 01:01:24.300
What is it?

01:01:27.290 --> 01:01:28.290
They're bonding.

01:01:29.730 --> 01:01:31.701
It's a real

01:01:31.702 --> 01:01:33.968
lovefest in there right now.

01:01:38.800 --> 01:01:39.800
Sir?

01:01:40.699 --> 01:01:42.640
The final phase of the plan

01:01:43.888 --> 01:01:45.055
can now begin.

01:01:46.740 --> 01:01:47.740
Delgado out.

01:01:51.760 --> 01:01:52.929
What did he say?

01:01:52.930 --> 01:01:53.780
He's happy.

01:01:53.780 --> 01:01:54.613
For real?

01:01:54.614 --> 01:01:55.929
Ha ha ha, dead cereal.

01:01:55.930 --> 01:01:57.409
Jesus, that guy is hard to read.

01:01:57.410 --> 01:01:58.360
What kinda plan is this?

01:01:58.361 --> 01:01:59.949
Who cares? Let's get outta here.

01:01:59.950 --> 01:02:01.036
But shouldn't we wait until...

01:02:01.037 --> 01:02:02.559
No, we deserve a night off.

01:02:02.560 --> 01:02:04.239
These people are making me suicidal.

01:02:04.240 --> 01:02:07.749
I want to drown myself in my own urine.

01:02:07.750 --> 01:02:11.375
Come on, let's go home
and hug our families.

01:02:13.250 --> 01:02:14.083
You're sure.

01:02:14.084 --> 01:02:16.809
Positive, I've
never seen Delgado so happy.

01:02:16.810 --> 01:02:17.810
I'm going in.

01:02:19.413 --> 01:02:21.903
And, Paige, good work.

01:02:22.770 --> 01:02:24.659
I'm going to tell our boss everything

01:02:24.660 --> 01:02:26.799
you've done for our cause.

01:02:26.800 --> 01:02:27.963
Thank you, sir.

01:02:34.517 --> 01:02:37.184
Here I go, staggering my exit.

01:02:44.520 --> 01:02:46.499
Oh hey, can I borrow your phone?

01:02:46.500 --> 01:02:47.500
Yeah.

01:02:48.340 --> 01:02:49.638
Thank you.

01:02:49.639 --> 01:02:51.773
I'm gonna go look at the stars.

01:02:55.110 --> 01:02:57.533
Hey, it's your dad.

01:02:58.430 --> 01:02:59.380
You free tomorrow?

01:02:59.381 --> 01:03:00.993
I'd like to talk to you.

01:03:02.433 --> 01:03:03.433
See you then.

01:03:15.640 --> 01:03:16.640
Hey.

01:03:18.790 --> 01:03:21.951
I meant to tell you, I
started reading this...

01:03:53.570 --> 01:03:55.199
We need to talk.

01:03:55.200 --> 01:03:56.849
Loud cheers at the president's

01:03:56.850 --> 01:03:59.289
rally last night as he vowed to quote,

01:03:59.290 --> 01:04:02.029
Punch the bejesus out
of anyone sticking up

01:04:02.030 --> 01:04:04.449
for headbanders trying to strike fear

01:04:04.450 --> 01:04:07.149
into the hearts of normal Americans.

01:04:07.150 --> 01:04:10.019
The president said some
loners were great people

01:04:10.020 --> 01:04:13.379
but they had to be saved
from their quote, weird life,

01:04:13.380 --> 01:04:15.843
and that he was the only
one who could do that.

01:04:21.110 --> 01:04:22.293
It's been disabled.

01:04:23.240 --> 01:04:24.999
Do you have his phone?

01:04:25.000 --> 01:04:26.619
Your phone.

01:04:26.620 --> 01:04:28.770
What the hell, man, that's new!

01:04:29.670 --> 01:04:31.009
Now it's old.

01:04:31.010 --> 01:04:32.779
What do you mean missing?

01:04:32.780 --> 01:04:35.740
Off the radar, sir,
he's not at home, and

01:04:37.310 --> 01:04:39.459
there's no signal from his cellphone.

01:04:39.460 --> 01:04:44.239
I apologize for the
impolite greeting here today,

01:04:44.240 --> 01:04:46.949
but the hood was absolutely necessary,

01:04:46.950 --> 01:04:49.409
and it's of utmost importance you not know

01:04:49.410 --> 01:04:50.949
the sight of this meeting.

01:04:50.950 --> 01:04:53.549
This white tarped popup room

01:04:53.550 --> 01:04:55.693
could in fact be anywhere in the world.

01:04:58.170 --> 01:05:00.639
We're in the City of Industry,

01:05:00.640 --> 01:05:02.329
right off the Pomona Freeway at the corner

01:05:02.330 --> 01:05:04.569
of Newquist and Proctor.

01:05:04.570 --> 01:05:07.563
Taser Ted here, he had
the GPS on the whole way.

01:05:14.330 --> 01:05:15.330
GPS?

01:05:17.040 --> 01:05:18.040
Leave us.

01:05:19.040 --> 01:05:21.249
I'm in, what's her name again?

01:05:21.250 --> 01:05:22.250
Clara.

01:05:23.258 --> 01:05:24.258
Last name?

01:05:25.483 --> 01:05:27.397
We never got that far.

01:05:30.910 --> 01:05:33.060
What's up with all
the Swedish furniture?

01:05:35.160 --> 01:05:37.869
Let me get to the point, Mr. Chalk.

01:05:37.870 --> 01:05:39.939
You're in danger.

01:05:39.940 --> 01:05:41.829
And we're here to help you.

01:05:41.830 --> 01:05:43.299
Now listen to me carefully.

01:05:43.300 --> 01:05:46.259
My name is Mr. Tessman.

01:05:46.260 --> 01:05:48.899
I work for someone who
has a vested interest

01:05:48.900 --> 01:05:51.659
in the failure of the War on Loneliness.

01:05:51.660 --> 01:05:54.959
Now what happens in the next
few days is going to have

01:05:54.960 --> 01:05:57.659
a large impact on that war's future,

01:05:57.660 --> 01:06:00.303
and you are going to play
a very large part in it.

01:06:01.370 --> 01:06:05.749
Don't be so sure, I'm
actually surprisingly lazy.

01:06:05.750 --> 01:06:07.473
You're already deeply involved.

01:06:08.460 --> 01:06:10.569
And my people had nothing to do with it.

01:06:10.570 --> 01:06:12.043
But like I said before,

01:06:13.000 --> 01:06:14.550
we're going to try to help you.

01:06:15.878 --> 01:06:17.709
Yeah, I'm going to
need to know who you're

01:06:17.710 --> 01:06:19.653
working for, Mr. Tessman.

01:06:21.310 --> 01:06:22.523
Let's just say,

01:06:24.060 --> 01:06:25.970
it is an individual

01:06:26.870 --> 01:06:29.999
who has a deep philosophical
opposition to the government's

01:06:30.000 --> 01:06:33.589
attack of a person's right to stand alone.

01:06:33.590 --> 01:06:37.699
Yeah, well, lots of people
are opposed to this program.

01:06:37.700 --> 01:06:40.123
What makes your boss so different?

01:06:42.140 --> 01:06:44.113
Well for one thing, resources.

01:06:45.180 --> 01:06:46.180
Money?

01:06:47.670 --> 01:06:48.823
And people.

01:06:50.460 --> 01:06:53.289
We've been able to
place some collaborators

01:06:53.290 --> 01:06:54.609
at very high levels.

01:06:54.610 --> 01:06:56.409
The information which they've gathered

01:06:56.410 --> 01:06:57.903
will be your salvation.

01:06:59.150 --> 01:07:01.513
Assuming you agree to help us.

01:07:03.490 --> 01:07:04.590
Is this her address?

01:07:06.180 --> 01:07:07.180
Yeah, that's it.

01:07:08.190 --> 01:07:09.399
Weird.

01:07:09.400 --> 01:07:10.400
What?

01:07:11.220 --> 01:07:14.369
Usually they give a
pretty good description.

01:07:14.370 --> 01:07:15.823
But this is just three words.

01:07:18.300 --> 01:07:20.536
To make room.

01:07:23.850 --> 01:07:26.439
I still need to know who this us is.

01:07:26.440 --> 01:07:27.857
Who am I agreeing to help?

01:07:28.320 --> 01:07:31.379
If I were to say the word recluse,

01:07:31.380 --> 01:07:33.159
what name would spring to mind?

01:07:33.160 --> 01:07:34.160
Brown.

01:07:35.050 --> 01:07:35.950
Brown?

01:07:35.951 --> 01:07:37.433
Brown recluse spider.

01:07:37.434 --> 01:07:39.449
Oh the spider, no, a person.

01:07:39.450 --> 01:07:41.099
There is the,

01:07:41.100 --> 01:07:42.339
the biggest loner of all time.

01:07:42.340 --> 01:07:44.714
That guy who would stay
in his house all the time

01:07:44.715 --> 01:07:45.899
and had the tissue boxes for shoes,

01:07:45.900 --> 01:07:46.810
but you can't possibly mean him.

01:07:46.811 --> 01:07:49.489
I do, I do, I am talking about

01:07:49.490 --> 01:07:51.969
the most famous, the
most accomplished loner

01:07:51.970 --> 01:07:56.019
in world history, Howard Randolph Hughes.

01:07:56.020 --> 01:07:57.819
Who has been dead for many years.

01:07:57.820 --> 01:07:59.899
But his progeny live on in his name.

